Class — the blueprint

A class is like a template or blueprint for creating things.

Think of it this way:

A class = design of a house
It defines what properties and behaviors the house will have

class Person {
  // properties and methods will go here
}


Object — the actual instance

An object is a real instance created from a class.

Class = blueprint
Object = actual thing built from that blueprint
let p1 = new Person();
let p2 = new Person();

Constructor — the initializer

A constructor is a special method inside a class that runs automatically when you create an object.

Its job:

Initialize object properties
Set starting values

class Person {
  constructor(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }
}

Now when you create an object:

let p1 = new Person("Ali", 25);

The constructor runs automatically.


What does this.name = name mean?

This is the key line you asked about.

Breakdown:
this.name = name;
this → refers to the current object being created
name (right side) → the parameter passed into the constructor
this.name → the property of the object
So it means:

“Take the value passed into the constructor (name) and store it inside this object’s name property.”